item.title: California governor signs law banning voter ID requirements; 'Joker is in Charge', says Elon Musk
item.description: Elon Musk criticized California's new law banning local governments from requiring voter ID, expressing concerns about election security and voter fraud. His comments sparked mixed reactions on social media, highlighting a divide on the issue. The law was enacted following Huntington Beach's voter ID mandate and aims to counter conservative initiatives.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: NYC's oldest lesbian bar sues 'angry woke' for $40 million over racism allegations
item.description: Henrietta Hudson, a historic lesbian bar in the US, has filed a $40 million lawsuit against activist Anne Marie Siroun Bompart, claiming her social media accusations of racism have damaged their reputation. The bar alleges Bompart's claims led to event cancellations and tarnished their long-standing community contributions. Bompart, facing bans from multiple bars, plans to represent herself in court.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Must level playing field': California bans legacy admissions in higher education institutions
item.description: California governor Gavin Newsom signed a bill banning legacy preferences in private college admissions, effective fall 2025. This law addresses equity in admissions and ensures compliance through annual reports. California joins Maryland in prohibiting legacy admissions at private, non-profit universities, reflecting public opinion against alumni influence.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: JD Vance draws comparison between 'abortion' and 'slavery' in controversial audio clip
item.description: Senator JD Vance's comparison of abortion to slavery has fueled criticism from reproductive rights advocates. During his campaign, Vance has promoted a nationwide abortion ban and voiced support for federal measures to limit access. Kamala Harris has strongly criticized Vanceâ€™s views and their potential implications.

item.title: 3 dead, 15 injured in Shanghai knife attack
item.description: In Shanghai, a knife attack at a supermarket resulted in three fatalities and 15 injuries. The attacker, a 37-year-old man named Lin, was detained. Recent incidents, including attacks in Shenzhen and Suzhou, have raised security concerns. Authorities frequently attribute such violence to mental illness.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Lines for fresh water, communities cut off: Hurricane Helene leaves trail of destruction with over 130 dead, many missing
item.description: Hurricane Helene has devastated the southern US, causing 133 deaths across six states, with 600 people still missing. Western North Carolina is particularly affected, suffering from severe floods, disrupted communication, and critical infrastructure damage. Emergency teams continue rescue operations, while aid delivery efforts have begun to support the hardest-hit regions.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Trump says he coordinated with Musk to deploy Starlink; White House counters
item.description: Former President Donald Trump claimed he coordinated with Elon Musk to deploy Starlink systems to hurricane-hit North Carolina, accusing the Biden administration of delays. The White House refuted this, affirming that deployment was already underway with 40 systems in use and 140 more on the way.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Rockets target US troops at Iraq's Baghdad airport amid rising tensions in middle east
item.description: Three rockets were launched at Baghdad International Airport, targeting the Victory Base housing US troops. Two were intercepted by the base's defence system, and the third landed near the Counter Terrorism Service Command. No casualties were reported and air traffic was unaffected.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Helene disrupts presidential race as Trump, Harris address disaster
item.description: Hurricane Helene wreaks havoc in the US southeast, affecting key states just weeks before Election Day. Trump visits Georgia, promotes Starlink aid, while Harris cuts short her campaign to focus on recovery efforts. The storm's economic impact and political responses raise tensions as both presidential candidates strive to show leadership amidst the crisis.

item.title: Bangladesh interim govt faces flak for dissolution of textbook review panel
item.description: Transparency International Bangladesh criticizes the interim government's dissolution of a committee tasked with revising textbooks, viewing it as a troubling compromise with radical elements. TIB asserts this decision undermines the vision of a non-discriminatory and non-sectarian 'New Bangladesh.'

item.title: 'Shazam!' star Zachary Levi endorses Trump in move he called 'career suicide'
item.description: Zachary Levi, known for his role as Shazam, endorsed Donald Trump during a political event with Robert F Kennedy Jr and Tulsi Gabbard in Michigan. Raised in a conservative family, Levi highlighted his disillusionment with the current political system. He acknowledged potential career risks in Hollywood but stated his endorsement aligns with his values, garnering support from fans.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Baseball's all-time hit king and controversial figure Pete Rose dies at 83
item.description: Legendary MLB player Pete Rose passed away at age 83. Known as 'Charlie Hustle,' he set numerous records, including the all-time hit record. His career faced controversy due to gambling, leading to a permanent MLB ban. Despite this, his legacy in baseball remains significant.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Plug cord into phone': Trump claims Kamala 'fake and staged' photo of hurricane Helene response briefing
item.description: Former President Trump accused Vice President Kamala Harris of staging a photo showing her during a call about Hurricane Helene recovery efforts. Trump pointed out an apparent discrepancy, suggesting the photo was fake. Harrisâ€™s post on social media detailed federal actions to support impacted areas, with over 3,300 federal personnel deployed for relief operations.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Hezbollah is a political party, not a terrorist group': Iran's ambassador to India Iraj Elahi
item.description: Iran's ambassador to India, Iraj Elahi, refutes Israel's labeling of Hezbollah as a terrorist group, stating it justifies violence. He regards the death of Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah in an Israeli strike as a significant loss. Elahi urges global efforts to halt Israeli invasions in the Middle East to ease regional tensions.

The storm has caused severe damage across multiple states, leaving many unaccounted for. item.title: Californiaâ€™s landmark AI safety bill blocked by governor amid tech industry backlash
item.description: California governor Gavin Newsom has vetoed a pivotal AI safety bill amid significant opposition from tech giants like OpenAI, Google, and Meta. The legislation sought strict safety measures but faced criticism for potentially hindering innovation. Newsom plans to seek expert input for future safeguards against AI risks.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Judge overturns Georgiaâ€™s six-week abortion law, reinstates 22-week limit
item.description: A Georgia judge has invalidated the state's six-week abortion ban, deeming it unconstitutional. This decision allows abortions up to 22 weeks, overturning a restrictive 2019 law. Judge Robert McBurney emphasized women's autonomy and rights over their own bodies, noting that fetal survival outside the womb should be a crucial consideration.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Biden presses for cease-fire, urges Netanyahu to abandon planned Lebanon invasion after Nasrallah killing
item.description: US President Joe Biden has urged Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to halt plans for a potential invasion of southern Lebanon after Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah's assassination. Amidst expectations of Israeli military action, Biden called for a cease-fire, emphasizing restraint. This request highlights the ongoing tension between Biden and Netanyahu regarding Israel's response to Hezbollah's retaliatory attacks.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'I was...': US President Joe Biden gets defensive over reporter question on Hurricane Helene
item.description: President Biden addressed concerns about his absence from Washington during Hurricane Helene. He assured the federal government's commitment to aid victims and detailed ongoing relief efforts. Biden emphasized staying connected with local leaders and deployed over 3,600 personnel. He urged residents to heed emergency warnings and pledged to support the affected areas until recovery is complete.
